modules.comments:
Like Data.Array but keeps unique values. Inspired by haskell's Data.Set.Ordered

Some of Data.Array's functions are not included because they don't make
sense when there are already unique values:
nub, nubEq, nubBy, replicate

For documentation of functions look in Data.Array

Not implemented (and why):
* Apply, Bind, Traversable — require Functor, which is intentionally omitted (map is not structure-preserving)
* some, many — require Alternative + Lazy, not applicable to OSet
* group, group', groupBy — trivial for unique elements (every group is a singleton)

declarations.comments:
Maps over the values in a set.

This operation is not structure-preserving for sets, so is not a valid Functor. An example case: mapping const x over a set with n > 0 elements will result in a set with one element.
declarations.title: map

declarations.comments:
Fold a data structure, accumulating values in some `Monoid`,
combining adjacent elements using the specified separator.

For example:

```purescript
> intercalate ", " ["Lorem", "ipsum", "dolor"]
= "Lorem, ipsum, dolor"

> intercalate "*" ["a", "b", "c"]
= "a*b*c"

> intercalate [1] [[2, 3], [4, 5], [6, 7]]
= [2, 3, 1, 4, 5, 1, 6, 7]
```
declarations.title: intercalate

declarations.comments:
`any f` is the same as `or <<< map f`; map a function over the structure,
and then get the disjunction of the results.
declarations.title: any

declarations.comments:
`all f` is the same as `and <<< map f`; map a function over the structure,
and then get the conjunction of the results.
declarations.title: all

declarations.comments:
Fold a data structure from the right, keeping all intermediate results
instead of only the final result. Note that the initial value does not
appear in the result (unlike Haskell's `Prelude.scanr`).

```purescript
scanr (+) 0 [1,2,3] = [6,5,3]
scanr (flip (-)) 10 [1,2,3] = [4,5,7]
```
declarations.title: scanr

declarations.comments:
Fold a data structure from the left, keeping all intermediate results
instead of only the final result. Note that the initial value does not
appear in the result (unlike Haskell's `Prelude.scanl`).

```purescript
scanl (+) 0  [1,2,3] = [1,3,6]
scanl (-) 10 [1,2,3] = [9,7,4]
```
declarations.title: scanl
